Lecture 10

Multivariate Regression

Prior to this lecture, you should have read chapter 10 of Regression and Other Stories.

Example data

Five hundred students enrolled in a course. Students were randomly assigned to one of three instructors. Students took a pretest at the beginning of the term to test their initial knowledge of the topic. Prior to taking the final exam, students were asked how much time they spent studying for the course each week.

Here is a scatter plot showing the relationship to students’ pretest scores and their scores on the final exam:

Here is a scatter plot showing the relationship between the amount of time students spent studying and their scores on the final exam:

Here are the student scores for each instructor, with average indicated by horizonal lines.

Higher test scores seem to be associated with more time spent studying, higher pretest scores, and with being in Krumholz’s class.

Estimating a multiple regression model

Let’s predict final exam scores based on pretest scores, weekly time spent studying, and instructor.

model <- lm(final_score ~ pretest + time_studying + instructor,
            data = exam_data)

You’ll get the same results in R as in Excel:

summary(model)
